That became an all-digital system.

01:45:15.560 --> 01:45:16.650
The hybrid systems went away.

01:45:16.650 --> 01:45:22.929
The high capacity computers, they could fit
in one good size room everything they needed,

01:45:22.929 --> 01:45:28.950
and were able to get much more digital displays
for the crews.

01:45:28.950 --> 01:45:32.960
Sometimes what they used to do for the imagery
of the crew in the early days is they would

01:45:32.960 --> 01:45:37.199
actually drive a camera across a simulated
scene because you couldn't generate the scene.

01:45:37.199 --> 01:45:42.480
By the time they got the sail facility developed
they were able to do scene generation with

01:45:42.480 --> 01:45:48.239
fairly high computers.

01:45:48.239 --> 01:45:49.820
Now everything could almost be tabletop.

01:45:49.820 --> 01:45:54.430
I mean it is just so dramatic as how this
evolved over the years.

01:45:54.430 --> 01:45:58.199
The one thing they had at Rockwell that never
got replaced, though, is they also were able

01:45:58.199 --> 01:46:02.330
to put into the loop actual hydraulic systems.

01:46:02.330 --> 01:46:08.389
When they were doing entry they could turn
on aero surfaces and hydraulics with simulated

01:46:08.389 --> 01:46:09.579
loads.

01:46:09.579 --> 01:46:13.580
And you always knew when they were doing it
because the high pitch scream of the APUs,

01:46:13.580 --> 01:46:16.630
when they were doing it, you could hear two
blocks away.

01:46:16.630 --> 01:46:17.630
OK.

01:46:17.630 --> 01:46:18.630
Last question.

01:46:18.630 --> 01:46:32.530
Sir, I was wondering if you could give kind
of a concept of the cost of developing the

01:46:32.530 --> 01:46:35.571
software either in man hours or in comparison
of what they spent on the hardware.

01:46:35.571 --> 01:46:41.250
Well, the initial development of the system
probably involved the equivalent of 15 or

01:46:41.250 --> 01:46:49.560
20 full time people for a few years.

01:46:49.560 --> 01:46:55.350
And this was to develop the algorithms and
support the validation.

01:46:55.350 --> 01:46:59.869
The actual flight software was actually produced
by IBM separately.

01:46:59.869 --> 01:47:04.349
And they had a small team of people that would
take the detail design specifications and

01:47:04.349 --> 01:47:19.270
create 

01:47:19.270 --> 01:47:21.610
the software.

01:47:21.610 --> 01:47:36.990
It is a big effort but a very small part of
the cost of developing a Shuttle.

01:47:36.990 --> 01:47:40.150
I mean you measure the Shuttle in billions.

01:47:40.150 --> 01:47:43.540
You measure the flight software development
in millions.

01:47:43.540 --> 01:47:50.949
One thing that I remember when the software
was developed and we were working and validating

01:47:50.949 --> 01:47:56.660
it, IBM wanted every line of code change in
million dollars.

01:47:56.660 --> 01:48:02.159
A million dollars for one line of code change
because they had to verify the whole software.

01:48:02.159 --> 01:48:06.940
That is why you would never, unless there
was a flight critical thing, do that.

01:48:06.940 --> 01:48:14.590
NASA wanted generally, whenever possible,
to aggregate changes for a year or maybe two

01:48:14.590 --> 01:48:15.599
years sometimes.

01:48:15.599 --> 01:48:20.070
And then put them in there just for that reason
because there was this huge cost of revalidating.

01:48:20.070 --> 01:48:22.360
And that was the IBM cost.

01:48:22.360 --> 01:48:25.640
It would be a cost to bringing us back in
to certify that, too.

01:48:25.640 --> 01:48:29.160
Well, it worked and you should be very proud
of it, you and your colleagues.

01:48:29.160 --> 01:48:30.160
Thank you very much, Phil.

01:48:30.160 --> 01:48:31.160
Thank you.

01:48:31.160 --> 01:48:31.161
[APPLAUSE]

